# Python Dependency Management Standards

## Context
- When managing Python project dependencies
- When setting up development environments
- When handling dependency conflicts
- When updating package versions
- When ensuring reproducibility

## Requirements

### Dependency Management
- Use Poetry for dependency management:
  ```toml
  # pyproject.toml
  [tool.poetry]
  name = "project-name"
  version = "0.1.0"
  description = "Project description"
  authors = ["Author <author@example.com>"]
  packages = [{include = "src"}]

  [tool.poetry.dependencies]
  python = "^3.10"
  pandas = "^2.0.0"
  numpy = "^1.24.0"
  scikit-learn = "^1.3.0"

  [tool.poetry.group.dev.dependencies]
  pytest = "^7.4.0"
  black = "^23.0.0"
  mypy = "^1.5.0"
  pytest-cov = "^4.1.0"

  [tool.poetry.group.docs.dependencies]
  sphinx = "^7.0.0"
  sphinx-rtd-theme = "^2.0.0"
  ```

### Version Constraints
- Use semantic versioning constraints:
  ```toml
  # Good: Specific version constraints
  [tool.poetry.dependencies]
  pandas = "^2.0.0"  # Allow patch and minor updates
  numpy = "~1.24.0"  # Allow only patch updates
  scikit-learn = ">=1.3.0,<2.0.0"  # Explicit range
  ```

### Dependency Groups
- Organize dependencies by purpose:
  ```toml
  # Good: Well-organized dependency groups
  [tool.poetry.group.dev.dependencies]
  pytest = "^7.4.0"
  black = "^23.0.0"
  mypy = "^1.5.0"

  [tool.poetry.group.test.dependencies]
  pytest-cov = "^4.1.0"
  pytest-mock = "^3.10.0"
  hypothesis = "^6.0.0"

  [tool.poetry.group.docs.dependencies]
  sphinx = "^7.0.0"
  sphinx-rtd-theme = "^2.0.0"
  ```

### Lock Files
- Maintain lock files for reproducibility:
  ```bash
  # Update dependencies
  poetry update

  # Install dependencies
  poetry install

  # Export requirements
  poetry export -f requirements.txt --output requirements.txt
  ```

### Virtual Environments
- Use Poetry's virtual environment management:
  ```bash
  # Create new environment
  poetry env use python3.10

  # Activate environment
  poetry shell

  # Run commands in environment
  poetry run pytest
  ```

